<DOC><DOCNO> AP890519-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0805EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0502 05-19 0736</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0750</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Drench South, Midwest</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Twisters in ...' to CORRECT that homes weredestroyed in East Feliciana Parish, sted East Baton Rouge.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms lingered in much of the South andMidwest today, and rescuers in New Jersey used an Army vehicledesigned for fording rivers in wartime to evacuate residents fromflooded areas.   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 a.m. EDTincluded more than 5 inches at Fort Myers, Fla., nearly 2 inches atBiloxi, Miss., and 1} inches at Baton Rouge, La.   In northern New Jersey, rescuers used rowboats, canoes and evenan old World War II amphibious vehicle Thursday to help evacuatePassaic County residents from their homes as the Passaic Riverremained at flood levels. More than 600 people have been displacedby flooding, emergency officials said.   Rain still fell in parts of Louisiana today, where state policesaid roads, highways and ferry services were closed in 13 parisheslate Thursday night because of flooding. The closures were along a250-mile stretch extending from Shreveport in northwest Louisianato the capital city of Baton Rouge.   In south Louisiana, St. Landry Parish sheriff's deputies saidlightning probably started a house fire early Thursday that lefttwo children dead near Opelousas.   Twisters in East and West Baton Rouge, St. Landry, Iberville andLafayette parishes downed trees and power lines and damagedbuildings Thursday. At least four homes were destroyed in EastFeliciana Parish, said Sheriff Randy Maglone.   Skies in Oklahoma began clearing today as the violent stormsthat claimed at least one life and spawned as many as fourtornadoes in northeast Oklahoma on Thursday moved out of the state.   Authorities said a teen-ager drowned Wednesday when he was sweptinto Duck Pond Creek while trying to cross it during heavy rainsabout six miles north of Elmwood in western Oklahoma.   Tornadoes ravaged much of the northeastern area of the stateThursday afternoon, damaging as many as 40 homes and injuring oneperson.   On Thursday, torrential rains dumped nearly a foot of water onthe Houston area, overwhelming drainage bayous and turning somelow-lying subdivisions into huge lakes. Residents of about 100homes fled by boat when Greens Bayou overcame its banks.   Four tornadoes touched down in Arkansas Thursday night,destroying several homes and downing power lines. Four tornadoesalso were reported in Kansas Thursday.   Heavy rain and thunderstorms drenched much of Mississippi, withseveral areas in the southern part of the state reporting 3 to 7inches of rain. In Brookhaven, more than 6 inches fell from 3:30 to8:30 p.m. Rainfall of up to 8 inches was common south of FortMyers, Fla.   Showers and thunderstorms also hit northwest Tennessee, westernKentucky, southern and central Missouri, central Iowa, easternMinnesota, northern Wisconsin and upper Michigan. Showers werescattered over eastern Montana.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extendingfrom the central and eastern Gulf Coast across much of theMississippi and Ohio valleys into the upper Great Lakes; showersand some thunderstorms across the northern Rockies and the northernPlains; snow showers in parts of Montana; and rain showers acrossnorthwest Washington state.   Predicted highs: 40s in parts of Montana; 50s and 60s in thenorthern Pacific Coast and the eastern slopes of the northern andcentral Rockies; 90s in the desert Southwest and the western thirdof Texas; and 70s or 80s across much of the rest of the nation.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 24degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 85 at Laredo, Texas.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 70 cloudy; Boston 55 fair; Buffalo 62 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 63 fair; Cincinnati 66 cloudy; Cleveland 60cloudy; Detroit 62 partly cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 59 fair;Philadelphia 57 fair; Pittsburgh 65 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine51 fair; Washington 62 partly cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 59 fair; Chicago 69 showery; Dallas-FortWorth 74 cloudy; Denver 59 fair; Des Moines 61 showery;Indianapolis 67 cloudy; Kansas City 60 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul60 foggy; Nashville 74 cloudy; New Orleans 72 thunderstorms; St.Louis 70 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 45 partly cloudy; LasVegas 76 windy; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 82 fair; Salt LakeCity 48 windy; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle48 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 63 fair; Toronto 57 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>